anterbury Tales. This unique interdisciplinary approach shows how physical and ideological mobilities shape and are shaped by geographical, ecological, sociopolitical, and gendered identities. As human and more-than-human bodies cross borders and dissolve boundaries, they contribute to a fluid, permeable, and hybrid world that challenges traditional perceptions of boundedness, security, and fixity. By examining this kinesis alongside contexts including medieval bridge building, economics, and biology, this book reveals a rich exchange between word and world. In the end, The Canterbury Tales emerges as an amalgam of lived experience and the poetic imagination that both chronicles and constructs a world in the process of becoming. SARAH BRECKENRIDGE WRIGHT is an assistant professor of English at DuquesneUniversity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIdentity (Philosophical concept) in literature. 0aTravel in literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBiology.  aBoundedness.  aChaucer's Canterbury Tales.  aCultural Geography.  aEcocriticism.  aEconomics.  aExpression.  aFluid.  aGendered Identities.  aHybrid World.  aIdentity.  aKinesis.  aMedieval Bridge Building.  aMetaphorically.  aMobility.  aMovement.  aPilgrims.  aTales.  aWord.  aWorld.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787446939?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787446939423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787446939/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles